The term "'''Expressionist Rococo'''" was first used in 1928 by Max Osborn to describe the Theater am Kurfürstendamm in Berlin designed by [[Oskar Kaufmann]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Der Architekt Oskar Kaufmann|last=Osborn|first=Max|publisher=F. E. Hübsch|year=1928|isbn=|location=Berlin|pages=XIII}}</ref> In difference to the original [[Rococo]] design Kaufmann emphasizes on the dynamic and movement as a whole concept. Asymmetrical details are subordinated to a large symmetrical frame.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Oskar Kaufmann Ein Theaterarchitekt zwischen Tradition und Moderne|last=Hansen|first=Hansen|publisher=Gbr. Mann Verlag|year=2001|isbn=3786123756|location=Berlin|pages=109}}</ref>  Other protagonists of this style were [[Hans Poelzig]],  Leo Nachtlicht and Gerhard Schliepstein.

